Title : 2014 Colorado elections
Text : {{ElectionsCO}}
A '''general election''' was held in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]] on November 4, 2014. All of Colorado's executive officers were up for election as well as a [[United States Senate]] seat and all of Colorado's seven seats in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. [[Primary election]]s were held on June 24, 2014.

==Governor and lieutenant governor==
{{main|2014 Colorado gubernatorial election}}

Incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Governor of Colorado|Governor]] [[John Hickenlooper]] and his [[Lieutenant Governor of Colorado|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Joseph García (U.S. politician)|Joseph García]] ran for re-election to a second term in office. They were unopposed for the Democratic nomination<ref name=renominate>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_25554780/flood-recovery-rallies-democrats-they-renominate-hick-udall|title=Flood recovery rallies Democrats as they renominate Hick, Udall|date=April 12, 2014|accessdate=April 13, 2014|work=[[The Denver Post]]|first=Alison|last=Noon}}</ref> In Colorado, gubernatorial candidates pick their running mates and they are elected on the same ticket.

The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] nominee was former U.S. Representative and nominee for governor [[2006 Colorado gubernatorial election|in 2006]] [[Bob Beauprez]], whose running mate was [[Douglas County, Colorado|Douglas County]] [[County commission|Commissioner]] Jill Repella.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_25250713/bob-beauprez-expected-announce-gop-gubernatorial-run|title=Bob Beauprez expected to announce GOP gubernatorial run|date=February 28, 2014|accessdate=March 3, 2014|work=The Denver Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_26070617/bob-beauprez-picks-douglas-county-leader-jill-rapella|title=Bob Beauprez picks Douglas County leader Jill Repella as running mate|date=July 1, 2014|accessdate=July 3, 2014|work=[[The Denver Post]]|first=Joey|last=Bunch}}</ref> He defeated [[Secretary of State of Colorado]] [[Scott Gessler]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.9news.com/news/article/355604/339/Amid-flood-Gessler-announces-bid-for-governor|title=Amid flood disaster, Scott Gessler announces bid for Colorado governor|date=17 September 2013|accessdate=19 September 2013|work=[[KUSA (TV)|9News Colorado]]|first=Brandon|last=Rittiman|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130920193657/http://www.9news.com/news/article/355604/339/Amid-flood-Gessler-announces-bid-for-governor|archive-date=20 September 2013|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=stateassembly>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_25553583/colorado-gop-pick-gov-hopefuls-what-could-be|title=Mike Kopp, Scott Gessler make GOP ballot in Colorado governor's race|date=April 12, 2014|accessdate=April 13, 2014|work=[[The Denver Post]]|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> former Minority Leader of the [[Colorado Senate]] [[Mike Kopp]]<ref name=stateassembly/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/10/01/mike-kopp-to-file-for-governors-race-today/101068/|title=Republican Mike Kopp to file for governor’s race today|date=October 1, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013|work=[[The Denver Post]]|first=Lynn|last=Bartels}}</ref> and former U.S. Representative and [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]] nominee for governor [[2010 Colorado gubernatorial election|in 2010]] [[Tom Tancredo]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_23306668/tancredo-running-colorado-governor|title=Former Rep. Tancredo running for Colorado governor|date=May 23, 2013|accessdate=May 25, 2013|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]}}</ref> in the primary election.

Libertarian Matthew Hess and his running mate Brandon Young,<ref>{{cite web|last=Bartels|first=Lynn|title=Oh, Hickenlooper has a challenger after all|date=3 February 2013|accessdate=4 February 2013|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/02/03/hickenlooper-challenger/90057/|work=Denver Post}}</ref> Greens Bill Bartlett and Harry Hempy<ref name=greenprimary>{{cite web|url=http://www.oppositionnews.org/articles/2014/q1/green-state-conventions-and-contested-primaries/|title=Green State Conventions and contested Primaries|date=March 25, 2014|accessdate=April 13, 2014|work=Opposition News}}</ref> and Independents Mike Dunafon, Mayor of [[Glendale, Colorado|Glendale]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2014/07/19/colorado-governors-race-picks-candidate-mike-dunafon-will-make-things-interesting/110954/|title=Colorado governor’s race picks up candidate Mike Dunafon, who will make things interesting|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=July 22, 2014|publisher=The Denver Post|author=Joey Bunch}}</ref> and Jim Rundberg<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=667757056609483|title=Candidate Working to be Colorado Governor in November!|date=February 8, 2014|accessdate=April 13, 2014|publisher=Facebook|last=Rundberg|first=Jim}}</ref> also ran.

