==Attorney General==
Incumbent Republican [[Colorado Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[John Suthers]] was term-limited and could not run for re-election to a third term in office.

===Republican primary===
The Republican nominee was Chief Deputy Attorney General [[Cynthia Coffman (politician)|Cynthia Coffman]], wife of U.S. Representative [[Mike Coffman]]. [[Mark Waller (politician)|Mark Waller]], former Minority Leader of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]], had been running, but he withdrew from the race. At the Republican state assembly on April 12, 2014, Coffman received the support of 69% of the delegates, while Waller received 30.7%, only narrowly passing the 30% needed to win a place on the primary ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2014/04/14/cynthia-coffman-amasses-almost-70-percent-gop-delegate-support-rep-mark-waller-just-30-percent/108145/|title=Cynthia Coffman amasses 69 percent of GOP delegate support, almost keeps Mark Waller off ballot|date=April 14, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=The Denver Post|author=Kurtis Lee}}</ref> On April 28, Waller announced that he was withdrawing from the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kdvr.com/2014/04/28/waller-ends-campaign-for-attorney-general-calls-for-gop-to-unify-behind-coffman/|title=Waller ends campaign for attorney general, calls for GOP to unify behind Coffman|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=KDVR|author=Eli Stokols}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2014/04/28/rep-mark-waller-citing-party-unity-withdraws-attorney-general-race/108551/|title=Rep. Mark Waller, citing party unity, withdraws from attorney general race|date=April 28, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=The Denver Post|author=Anthony Cotton}}</ref> [[Weld County, Colorado|Weld County]] [[District Attorney]] and nominee for the U.S. Senate [[United States Senate election in Colorado, 2010|in 2010]] [[Ken Buck]] was a speculated Republican candidate, but he declined in order to run for the U.S. Senate,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/08/07/ken-buck-files-paperwork-to-run-for-u-s-senate-in-2014/99119/|title=Republican Ken Buck files paperwork to run for U.S. Senate in 2014, after 2010 loss|date=August 7, 2013|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=The Denver Post|author=Kurtis Lee}}</ref> later dropping down to run for [[Colorado's 4th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/ken-buck-senate-cory-gardner-seat/|title=Ken Buck Drops Senate Bid to Run for Cory Gardner’s Seat|date=February 26, 2014|accessdate=February 26, 2014|work=Roll Call}}</ref> Attorney Mario Nicolais was also speculated to run, but he also declined to do so.<ref name=gordonnicolais>{{cite web|url=http://coloradopols.com/diary/19137/gordon-files-2014-secretary-of-state-bid-nicolais-for-ag|title=Gordon Files 2014 Secretary of State Bid; Nicolais For AG?|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=Colorado Pols}}</ref> He instead ran for the State Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/06/23/mario-nicolais-republican-mario-nicolais-thinks-hes-the-candidate-to-unseat-democrat-andy-kerr/97452/|title=Republican Mario Nicolais thinks he’s the candidate to unseat Democrat Andy Kerr|date=June 23, 2013|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=The Denver Post|author=Lynn Bartels}}</ref>

