===Democratic primary===
The Democratic nominee was former Deputy Attorney General and former [[District Attorney]] from the Seventeenth Judicial District Don Quick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://denver.cbslocal.com/2014/02/11/gay-marriage-emerges-as-issue-in-colorados-attorney-general-race/|title=Gay Marriage Emerges As Issue In Colorado’s Attorney General Race|date=February 11, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=CBS Denver|author=Ivan Moreno}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bwenergylaw.com/attorneys/documents/DonQuick.pdf|title=Biography: Don Quick|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=Beatty & Wozniack}}</ref> President of the [[Colorado Senate]] [[Morgan Carroll]] and District Attorneys Mitch Morrissey and Stan Garnett, who was the nominee for attorney general in 2010, were also speculated to run for the Democratic nomination, but declined to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2012/11/07/2014-ag-race/86124/|title=And now, onto 2014 and the race for Colorado attorney general|date=November 7, 2012|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=The Denver Post|author=Lynn Bartels}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2013/06/24/sen-morgan-carroll-says-no-to-ags-race/97494/|title=Sen. Morgan Carroll says "no" to AG’s race|date=June 24, 2013|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=The Denver Post|author=Lynn Bartels}}</ref>

